<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900904-0058</DOCNO><DOCID>900904-0058.</DOCID><HL>   Boeing Co. Receives $6 Billion Order   From Up-and-Coming Korean Carrier   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>09/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   BA FREST U.GPA MD NWA F.ABI F.ASP G.MES U.BA</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   Boeing Co. received a $6 billion order from AsianaAirlines, a new South Korean carrier.   Asiana placed firm orders for 27 Boeing aircraft valued atabout $3 billion and took options for 24 other planes, alsovalued at about $3 billion. The Asiana order, which wasexpected, is for six 747-400 passenger jets, three 747-400freighters, 10 767-300 jets and eight 737-400 jets. Theplanes are scheduled for delivery between 1993 and 1999.</LP><TEXT>   Separately, GPA Group Ltd. of Ireland, one of the world'slargest airliner-leasing companies, said it ordered as manyas 25 McDonnell Douglas MD-11 long-range aircraft, valued atabout $2.5 billion.   McDonnell Douglas couldn't be reached for comment, but GPAsaid the order comprises 13 firm orders and options on 12more MD-11s, due for delivery between 1995 and 1999. GrahamBoyd, GPA's managing director for new aircraft acquisitions,told reporters at the biennial Farnborough air show nearLondon that the company has no customers yet for the newplanes.   Also at the show, NWA Inc. announced it had convertedoptions on 75 Airbus Industrie A-320 commercial jets intofirm orders and had taken new options on 30 A-321 aircraft ina transaction valued at $4.6 billion. NWA, theMinneapolis-based parent of Northwest Airlines, said it wouldbe operating 100 A-320s by 1995. It already has eight of the150-seat short-haul to medium-haul airliners in operation.Northwest said the new options for the A-321 were convertibleinto A-320s before 1994 and were for delivery after 1996.   Airbus, a consortium comprising Aerospatiale of France,Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm G.m.b.H. of West Germany, BritishAerospace PLC and Construcciones Aeronauticas S.A. of Spain.,also announced at the air show that it may be profitable thisyear, which would be a first in the consortium's 20-yearhistory. Managing Director Jean Pierson said &quot;we might be inthe black&quot; for 1990, on revenue of about $5 billion. Hedeclined to elaborate on the sum. Airbus had said it wouldbecome profitable in 1994 or 1995.   He said the consortium probably will receive 300 to 350firm orders this year, down from last year's record 421orders but above the 270 orders forecast earlier this yearfor 1990.   Asiana, South Korea's No. 2 airline, is moving quickly toset up an international carrier network in the fast-growingAsian region. Formed in 1988 by South Korean industrialconglomerate Khumo Group, Asiana began by flying charterservices with leased jetliners. Emboldened by thegovernment's policy on airline deregulation, the carrier hassince moved into scheduled flights and began expandingoverseas last January. The Seoul-based company plans toexpand service to the U.S. in the fall of 1991, with otherroutes through Asia. The company has grown so fast that ithad to lure pilots away from its well-established rival,Korean Air, until Korean Air asked the government to ban thepractice. Asiana has a leased fleet of 10 Boeing 737-400s andtwo 737-500s.   Also at the airshow, British Airways PLC confirmed that ithas deferred decision on ordering new aircraft, partlybecause of the Persian Gulf crisis. A spokeswoman for thecompany, Britain's largest airline operator, said it wasoriginally due to announce around this time a decision onreplacing aging aircraft, primarily its fleet of eightDC-10s.</TEXT></DOC>